d displaying the Ten Commandments on courthouses, to demonstrate that the neutrality principle does not work in a pluralistic society. When defined by large, overarching principles of equality and liberty, neutrality fails to account for differences between groups and individuals. If, however, the Court drew on a variety of principles instead of a single notion of neutrality to decide whether or not laws facilitated or discouraged religious practices, the result could be a more equitable approach to religion clause cases.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aChurch and statezUnited StatesxInterpretation and construction. 0aFreedom of religionzUnited StatesxInterpretation and construction. 7aLAW / Courts.2bisacsh  aCommandments.  aRavitch.  aclause.  acontemporary.  acourthouses.  adebates.  ademonstrate.  adisplaying.  adoes.  adrawing.  ainterpretation.  aneutrality.  apluralistic.  aprayer.  aprinciple.  aprinciples.  areligion.  aschool.  asociety.  asuch.  athat.  aunpacks.  avarious.  awork.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814776766423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814776766/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK